title: Allow providers to be set for InferenceSession at construction
body: **Description**: Exposes`InferenceSession(..., providers=...)` for specifying provider at construction time. **Motivation and Context** I am testing some different backends (e.g. CUDA, TensorRT). If I build `onnxruntime` with TensorRT enabled, it is the default backend that is used, and loading the model takes significantly longer than with CUDA. I would like to select my providers before I start my session, so that way I can quickly test features with CUDA without paying the overhead of TensorRT loading (I presume due to TensorRT's optimizations?). I will later try to investigate how to optimize the model file for TensorRT, but for now, this is relatively easy. --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/microsoft/onnxruntime/2606)

title: Add schema for new Qops
body:
**Description**: Adding contrib ops schema for new quantization ops


Op | Notes
-- | --
QLinearAdd | u8 + u8 = u8 or s8 + s8 = s8   Takes scales and zero points for both inputs and output   and calculates 8 bit result
QLinearReduceMean | Takes 8 bit input, input and output scale and zero point and   produces 8 bit output per ReduceMean spec. uint8 support will be added to the   existing ReduceMean spec too, the difference being with this op the range of   output can be changed after the operation is performed. This is because after   ReduceMean the range is expected to reduce and requantizing the output in   this new range can bring accuracy benefits.
MulInteger | This is the basic 8 bit mul operator which takes 2 8 bit   inputs and produces        Int32        accumulated result    OR        if scales for input and output are given then produces the FP32 result
QLinearMul | Takes 2 8 bit inputs, their scales and zero points, output   scale and zero point and produces 8 bit output.
QLinearAveragePool | Takes 8 bit input, input and output scale and zero point and   produces 8 bit output per AveragePool spec. uint8 support will be added to   the existing AveragePool spec too, the difference being with this op the   range of output can be changed after the operation is performed. This is because   after AveragePool the range is expected to reduce and requantizing the output   in this new range can bring accuracy benefits.





**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: added cache version for nuphar JIT binaries
body:
Previously, when the user wrongfully loaded a JIT binary generated
from a Nuphar version different from the current used one, she
would get mysterious runtime failures, because we didn't perform
any version check on JIT binaries.

This change added cache versions to the Nuphar runtime and
JIT binaries. The Nuphar runtime will issue verbose message that
informs the user version-mismatch errors.

title: Reshape operator is generating wrong shape(!)
body:
**Description**: Fix a bug

**Motivation and Context**
A first party TF-to-Onnx model hit this  bug in Reshape operator.

The input data shape was:  (1, 20, 0, 512)
The requested shape was:  (  20, 0, 512)

This is a legal request. However, the Reshape op was mangling the requested shape to (20, 20, 512), which becomes an illegal request and causes ORT to error out.

title: MLAS: optimize QuantizeLinear
body:
**Description**:
This adds MLAS support to quantize a buffer using vector instructions for x86/x64/ARM64. This helper is now used for the QuantizeLinear and DynamicQuantizeLinear ops.

**Motivation and Context**
The old implementation had a significant cost from using the C runtime to do rounding and also didn't benefit from SIMD access. The new version should be bit identical to the old version. On x64 Windows, a sample quantized resnet50 model goes from 420ms->130ms.

The ARM32 build continues to the use the C runtime. A vectorized implementation is possible here too, but stick in ARMv7A NEON, such an implementation would require dropping to assembly and that's not worth it at this point.

An AVX+ implementation is also possible, but also not worth it at this point as the test quantized models are now dominated by GEMM and MlasQuantizeLinear is a small % of the runtime.

title: Fix the CUDNN_BN_MIN_EPSILON difference issue between cudnn7.3 and cudnn7.6
body:
In cudnn 7.6, CUDNN_BN_MIN_EPSILON is 0.0, however, it is 1e-5 in cudnn 7.3. It leads to the difference in LayerNorm with its original subgraph

cudnn 7.6
#define CUDNN_BN_MIN_EPSILON 0.0 /* Minimum epsilon allowed to be used in the Batch Normalization formula */
 
cudnn 7.3:

title: Populate ir version in testdata models
body:
**Description**: A subset of the models in testdata are missing an ir_version attribute. This change populates this ir_version to 3. It is already part of the onnx spec that the ir_version attribute is required.

**Motivation and Context**
This issue was identified because an additional check was added to validate that the ir version is populated and valid in the windowsai topic branch (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2413/files), addressing this issue (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2371).
Because of this change in the windowsai topic branch a variety of onnxruntime tests fail on model load when using these models. The reason this PR is targeted on master and not windowsai is because the requirement for populating ir_version is not new to windowsai and should be adhered to in master as well.

title: switch back order of session_state_ and execution_providers_ member declarations
body:
**Description**: switches back the order of the session_state_ and execution_providers_ member declarations in InferenceSession

**Motivation and Context**
execution_providers_ is being destroyed before session_state_, and in some winml test cases this causes work to be queued on an executioncontext after it had already been closed which results in an assertion failure. It seems like the order of declaration for these member variables were swapped in this PR (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2449). This causes the order that these members are constructed and destroyed to swap as well, violating the dependency that session_state_ has on execution_providers_.

body:
Need to remove -WHOLEARCHIVE. When this is removed, OrtGetWinMLAdapter isn't exposed as a DLL export anymore.

ORT uses python script to build generated_source.c which is a C file that exposes function interfaces to export in Onnxruntime.dll. gen_def.py is used to generate generated_source.c.

WinMLAdapterFactory.h is used in generated_source.c and is also used in Windows.AI.Machinelearning.dll code whenever OrtGetWInMLAdapter is used.
